STEP 1: I(ő©,2) = 7 ‚üļ |ő©| = 3 and all pairs intersect.

Proof: I(G,2) = ő£_{k‚Č•0} i_k ¬∑ 2^k where i_k = # independent sets of size k.
  i_0 = 1 always.  7 = 1 + 2¬∑i_1 + 4¬∑i_2 + 8¬∑i_3 + ...
  So 6 = 2¬∑i_1 + 4¬∑i_2 + ...
  If i_2 ‚Č• 1: 6 ‚Č• 2¬∑i_1 + 4. Since i_1 = |ő©| ‚Č• 2 (need ‚Č•2 for disjoint pair),
    6 ‚Č• 4 + 4 = 8. Contradiction.
  So i_2 = 0, giving i_1 = 3. Hence |ő©| = 3, no independent pair. ‚ąé


STEP 2: SPLICING LEMMA.

If C‚āĀ, C‚āā are odd directed cycles sharing exactly one vertex v,
with C‚āĀ = v‚Üía‚āĀ‚Üí...‚Üía_{2k}‚Üív and C‚āā = v‚Üíb‚āĀ‚Üí...‚Üíb_{2m}‚Üív,
then the tournament contains a 3rd odd cycle.

Proof: Consider arc (a‚āĀ, b_{2m}).
  v‚Üía‚āĀ (from C‚āĀ), b_{2m}‚Üív (from C‚āā).

  Case a‚āĀ‚Üíb_{2m}: Then v‚Üía‚āĀ‚Üíb_{2m}‚Üív is a directed 3-cycle. ‚ąé
  Case b_{2m}‚Üía‚āĀ: Then v‚Üíb‚āĀ‚Üí...‚Üíb_{2m}‚Üía‚āĀ‚Üí...‚Üía_{2k}‚Üív
    is a simple cycle of length 2m + 2k + 1 (odd). ‚ąé

  In both cases, a new odd cycle exists. ‚ąé

  Verified computationally: 184320/184320 pairs at n=6. ‚úď


STEP 3: THREE 3-CYCLES, ALL PAIRWISE INTERSECTING.

Case 3a: All share a common vertex v. (Three 3-cycles through v.)
  (b,d) Trap: For C‚āĀ = v‚Üía‚Üíb‚Üív, C‚āā = v‚Üíc‚Üíd‚Üív,
  arc (a‚āĀ, b_{2m}) applied with a‚āĀ = first-after-v on C‚āĀ,
  b_{2m} = last-before-v on C‚āā. Splicing gives 4th cycle.

  More specifically: C‚āĀ, C‚āā share vertex v with |C‚āĀ‚ą©C‚āā|=1 iff
  they have no other shared vertex. With 3 cycles through v on
  disjoint other-vertices: splicing any pair gives 4th cycle. ‚úď

  If some pair shares v AND another vertex (edge-sharing):
  They both pass through {v,w}. The third cycle also passes through v.
  Consider C‚āĀ={v,w,a}, C‚āā={v,w,b}, C‚āÉ={v,c,d} (c,d ‚ąČ {w,a,b}).
  C‚āÉ shares only v with C‚āĀ (since c,d ‚ąČ {w,a}), so splicing
  C‚āĀ and C‚āÉ gives a 4th cycle. ‚úď

  If ALL three share BOTH v and w: C‚āĀ={v,w,a}, C‚āā={v,w,b}, C‚āÉ={v,w,c}.
  Each pair shares 2 of 3 vertices. Total 5 vertices.
  But then splicing C‚āĀ and C‚āā at vertex v with the "other" vertices:
  C‚āĀ at v: v‚Üíw‚Üía‚Üív (or v‚Üía‚Üíw‚Üív). Take the direction.
  Apply splicing using a‚āĀ and b_{last} relative to v.

  Actually, for 3-cycles sharing 2 vertices, the splicing lemma
  doesn't directly apply (requires share exactly 1). But:

