STEP 3 continued: Share-2 analysis.

For three 3-cycles pairwise sharing ‚Č•2 vertices:
  C‚āĀ‚ą©C‚āā ‚Č• 2. Since |C‚āĀ| = |C‚āā| = 3, they share ‚Č•2 of 3 vertices.
  Similarly for other pairs.

  Claim: All three must share a common pair {v,w}.
  Proof: C‚āĀ = {a,b,c}. C‚āā shares ‚Č•2 with C‚āĀ.
    WLOG C‚āĀ‚ą©C‚āā ‚äá {a,b}. So C‚āā = {a,b,d}.
    C‚āÉ shares ‚Č•2 with C‚āĀ = {a,b,c} and ‚Č•2 with C‚āā = {a,b,d}.
    C‚āÉ has 3 elements from the universe.

    C‚āÉ‚ą©{a,b,c} ‚Č• 2 and C‚āÉ‚ą©{a,b,d} ‚Č• 2.

    If {a,b} ‚äā C‚āÉ: done, all three share {a,b}.
    If a ‚ąą C‚āÉ, b ‚ąČ C‚āÉ: C‚āÉ‚ą©{a,b,c} ‚Č• 2 requires c ‚ąą C‚āÉ.
      C‚āÉ‚ą©{a,b,d} ‚Č• 2 requires d ‚ąą C‚āÉ. So C‚āÉ = {a,c,d}.
      C‚āā‚ą©C‚āÉ = {a,b,d}‚ą©{a,c,d} = {a,d}. OK, ‚Č•2. ‚úď
      But C‚āĀ‚ą©C‚āÉ = {a,c}. ‚Č•2 ‚úď.
      Common to all 3: {a,b,c}‚ą©{a,b,d}‚ą©{a,c,d} = {a}. Only 1!
      So no common pair. Is this possible?

      CHECK: C‚āĀ={a,b,c}, C‚āā={a,b,d}, C‚āÉ={a,c,d}. Pairwise intersections:
        C‚āĀ‚ą©C‚āā = {a,b}, C‚āĀ‚ą©C‚āÉ = {a,c}, C‚āā‚ą©C‚āÉ = {a,d}. All ‚Č•2. ‚úď
        Total: 4 vertices {a,b,c,d}. Common vertex: a.

      All three cycles pass through vertex a!
      So we have 3 cycles through a: (b,d) trap / splicing applies.

